<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1673,2022]" pageId="3" pageNumber="569">
<taxonomicName box="[199,342,1673,1697]" class="Arachnida" family="Podocinidae" genus="Gnathosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="3" pageNumber="569" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[199,342,1673,1697]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="569">Gnathosoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[357,431,1673,1698]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 4" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1611,1634]" captionTargetBox="[160,1425,206,1580]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[150,1436,193,1590]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 4. Platyseius persicus. Female. 1. Dorsal idiosoma; 2 – 3. Details of some dorsal shield setae; 4. Epistome." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/258486/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="569">Figs 4</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[443,489,1674,1698]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 9" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1927,1950]" captionTargetBox="[159,1427,197,1901]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,193,1906]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 9. Platyseius persicus. Female. 5. Ventral idiosoma; 6. Tritosternum; 7. Sperm-reception structure; 8. Subcapitulum and palp; 9. Chelicera." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/258487/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="569">8–9</figureCitation>
). Epistome triramous anteriorly, tines subequal in size and denticulate apically (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 4" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1611,1634]" captionTargetBox="[160,1425,206,1580]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[150,1436,193,1590]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 4. Platyseius persicus. Female. 1. Dorsal idiosoma; 2 – 3. Details of some dorsal shield setae; 4. Epistome." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/258486/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="569">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). Subcapitulum with pair of internal malae, laterally slightly fringed, longer than corniculi; corniculi stout, hornlike, 52–54 long; setae 
<emphasis box="[429,457,1745,1769]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="569">h1</emphasis>
(91–95) and internal palp-trochanter setae (106–115) elongated and strip-like, only tapered near apex, 
<emphasis box="[360,389,1781,1805]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="569">h2</emphasis>
(50–52), 
<emphasis box="[497,525,1781,1805]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="569">h3</emphasis>
(62–64), 
<emphasis box="[633,660,1782,1805]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="569">pc</emphasis>
(47–50) simple; deutosternum with eight rows of denticles, including an apical straight row and seven multidentate posterior rows, anterior three rows connected, distance between fifth and sixth rows 1.45–1.5 that between fourth and fifth rows (
<figureCitation box="[855,926,1853,1878]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 9" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1927,1950]" captionTargetBox="[159,1427,197,1901]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,193,1906]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 9. Platyseius persicus. Female. 5. Ventral idiosoma; 6. Tritosternum; 7. Sperm-reception structure; 8. Subcapitulum and palp; 9. Chelicera." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/258487/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="569">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
). Basal segment of chelicera 106–114 long; second segment of chelicera 249–258 long, 45–50 wide; fixed digit of chelicera 
<date box="[1065,1135,1889,1914]" pageId="3" pageNumber="569" value="1976-04-07">7 4–76</date>
long, with relatively large subapical tooth followed by short ridge and ca. 12–15 minute denticles, pilus dentilis setiform, dorsal cheliceral seta slender, finely blunt; movable digit 95–103 long, with two small denticles on anterior third; with small hyaline flap behind movable digit. Palp segments with 
<date box="[678,776,1997,2022]" pageId="3" pageNumber="569" value="2014-05-02" valueMax="2014-06-02" valueMin="2014-05-02">2-5-6-14</date>
-15 setae, palp-tarsus apotele two tined.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/258487/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="570" targetBox="[159,1427,197,1901]" targetPageId="4">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1435,1927,1980]" pageId="4" pageNumber="570">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,317,1927,1950]" pageId="4" pageNumber="570">FIGURES 5–9</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[339,542,1928,1950]" class="Arachnida" family="Ascidae" genus="Platyseius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="4" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="persicus">
<emphasis box="[339,542,1928,1950]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="570">Platyseius persicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Female. 5. Ventral idiosoma; 6. Tritosternum; 7. Sperm-reception structure; 8. Subcapitulum and palp; 9. Chelicera.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption box="[151,1414,1927,1950]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/258488/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="571" targetBox="[156,1430,196,1901]" targetPageId="5">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1414,1927,1950]" box="[151,1414,1927,1950]" pageId="5" pageNumber="571">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,333,1927,1950]" pageId="5" pageNumber="571">FIGURES 10–14</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[346,540,1928,1950]" class="Arachnida" family="Ascidae" genus="Platyseius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="5" pageNumber="571" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="persicus">
<emphasis box="[346,540,1928,1950]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="571">Platyseius persicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Female. 10. Pretarsus I; 11. Leg I, excluding tarsus and pretarsus; 12–14. Legs II–IV.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,896]" pageId="6" pageNumber="572">
<emphasis box="[199,252,153,176]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="572">Legs</emphasis>
. All legs with ambulacrum and claws, those on legs I (16–18) smaller than others: II (61–63), III (72–74), IV (72–74); claws on legs II–IV flanked by relatively elongated flagellate paradactyli, shorter than half length of related 
<emphasis box="[235,277,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="572">ad1</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[334,377,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="572">pd1</emphasis>
setae; median lobe of their pulvilli acute. Lengths of legs I–IV 725–748, 601–612, 642–657, 853–881, respectively. Lengths of femora I 159–161, II 131–141, III 149–157, IV 206–216; genua I 128–131, 
<date pageId="6" pageNumber="572" value="1971-02">II 71</date>
–75, III 
<date box="[271,343,296,320]" pageId="6" pageNumber="572" value="1978-04-07">7 4–78</date>
, IV 103–106; tibiae I 133–136, 
<date box="[704,759,295,320]" pageId="6" pageNumber="572" value="1960-02">II 60</date>
–62, 
<date box="[815,877,296,320]" pageId="6" pageNumber="572" value="1971-03">III 71</date>
–74, IV 102–106; tarsi I 183–186, II 195–205, III 209–221, IV 295–300. Complement of setae on segments of legs I-II-III-IV: coxae 2-2-2-1; trochanters 6-5-5-5; femora (2 3/1 2/1 2)- (2 3/1 2/1 1) - (1 2/1 2/0 0) - (1 2/1 2/0 0); genua (2 3/2 3/1 2) - (2 3/1 2/0 2) - (2 2/1 2/0 1) - (2 2/1 3/0 1); tibiae (2 3/2 3/1 2) - (2 2/1 1/1 2) - (2 1/1 2/1 2) - (2 1/1 3/1 2); and those for tarsi II-IV: 18-18-18. Leg setae mostly short and relatively thickened, as in species diagnosis.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
